36
00:01:51,456 --> 00:01:56,360
So you're writing this code and people have to like ingest this all, have this going in their brain,

37
00:01:56,980 --> 00:01:59,822
and you don't want to break the compiler, you don't have too many rules,

38
00:02:00,523 --> 00:02:05,146
and they're the ones that they're experiencing these rules, but it's all transparent.

39
00:02:05,967 --> 00:02:09,410
Because video games are like this black box, right?

40
00:02:09,430 --> 00:02:11,952
You're giving it inputs and you're getting certain outputs,

41
00:02:11,972 --> 00:02:14,594
and you're trying to figure out what the rules are inside that box.

42
00:02:15,354 --> 00:02:18,695
And you get kind of a sense of what's going on, but it still

43
00:02:18,875 --> 00:02:19,975
surprises you in certain ways.

44
00:02:20,795 --> 00:02:25,176
But the ways that board games surprise you are through, you

45
00:02:25,236 --> 00:02:25,957
know all the rules.

46
00:02:25,997 --> 00:02:28,597
All the rules are in your head, and they're

47
00:02:28,617 --> 00:02:29,397
combined in new ways.

48
00:02:29,437 --> 00:02:31,418
And you're like, oh, that's a combination.

49
00:02:31,478 --> 00:02:33,518
I didn't think of using that card and that card together,

50
00:02:34,098 --> 00:02:35,479
or powers together, or whatever.

51
00:02:35,979 --> 00:02:40,080
And so it's this delight through emergence, not through

52
00:02:41,900 --> 00:02:44,481
finding out a new rule of what's going on under the hood.

53
00:02:45,361 --> 00:02:48,002
And the other thing about board games is its very raw design.

54
00:02:48,503 --> 00:02:52,845
You, as a designer, you've got a box of parts and instructions,

55
00:02:53,345 --> 00:02:54,806
and it's got to sing.

56
00:02:55,286 --> 00:02:58,768
It's got to entertain and pull all these emotions out

57
00:02:58,788 --> 00:02:59,089
of people.

58
00:02:59,869 --> 00:03:02,190
And we talk about a lot of emotions in video games,

59
00:03:02,210 --> 00:03:04,211
but there's a lot of emotion in board games.

60
00:03:05,300 --> 00:03:09,385
And I want to talk about some of the range of emotions you can have here.

61
00:03:09,425 --> 00:03:14,291
So you've got your werewolf mafia, and that's about, you know, and Secret Hiller.

62
00:03:16,073 --> 00:03:18,496
It's about deceit.

63
00:03:18,596 --> 00:03:23,842
Like what's the key moment in that game when you're like, it's when everyone believes you

64
00:03:24,042 --> 00:03:25,284
and you've got them all fooled.

65
00:03:26,911 --> 00:03:37,195
If you want to turn it up higher, I don't know if many of you have played this, but diplomacy is literally you have to stab all your friends in the back to win one at a time.

66
00:03:37,896 --> 00:03:42,777
Gain their trust, and then it's like Survivor. You're voting them off at the last minute and it's tragic.

67
00:03:43,238 --> 00:03:44,998
And do not play it. It will end friendships.

68
00:03:45,719 --> 00:03:48,800
Because that's the level of emotion that board games can create.

69
00:03:49,300 --> 00:03:52,481
And then there's, you know, Settlers. It's about reciprocity and trade.

70
00:03:53,622 --> 00:03:56,443
To get to Rideware, it's about prioritizing, you know, building your network.

71
00:03:57,003 --> 00:03:59,784
But in cooperative game, it's about altruism.

72
00:04:00,205 --> 00:04:05,027
It's about sacrificing for each other and collectively problem solving.

73
00:04:05,167 --> 00:04:09,549
And there's all these positive emotions around it and that's why I've been drawn to it.

74
00:04:09,609 --> 00:04:13,291
Because in board games, you test a lot and you test live.

75
00:04:13,891 --> 00:04:17,933
And I get driven by the energy that comes off of cooperative games.

76
00:04:19,089 --> 00:04:22,392
So where do we derive our emotions from?

77
00:04:22,552 --> 00:04:24,674
And a lot of times it's from other media.

78
00:04:25,174 --> 00:04:26,875
Let's see, there we go.

79
00:04:27,256 --> 00:04:30,759
Other media, so we watch these movies, TV shows, books,

80
00:04:31,139 --> 00:04:33,120
and they all have these moments, right,

81
00:04:33,621 --> 00:04:36,303
that we want to capture.

82
00:04:36,443 --> 00:04:40,366
And so often in video games, we think literally.

83
00:04:40,606 --> 00:04:43,609
We're like, okay, well, let's capture the scene

84
00:04:43,809 --> 00:04:46,531
or the visual or the cinematography.

85
00:04:47,332 --> 00:04:47,452
But.

86
00:04:49,262 --> 00:04:54,507
I think that what we really want, what we can get to with video games and with board

87
00:04:54,527 --> 00:04:56,328
games is the emotion at the core of it.

88
00:04:57,377 --> 00:04:59,199
And, because really what it comes down to

89
00:04:59,239 --> 00:05:01,460
is these scenarios, you know, am I doing a heist?

90
00:05:01,540 --> 00:05:03,802
Am I, you know, surviving on an island?

91
00:05:04,222 --> 00:05:05,583
Am I learning Kung Fu?

92
00:05:06,504 --> 00:05:07,585
You know, they get to the point of

93
00:05:07,865 --> 00:05:09,886
what would I do in that situation?

94
00:05:10,307 --> 00:05:12,588
Like, that's when I talk about the fantasy of the heist

95
00:05:12,648 --> 00:05:14,990
is like, we really ask ourselves this

96
00:05:15,310 --> 00:05:17,031
when we're looking at different media

97
00:05:17,071 --> 00:05:19,773
and you're like, yeah, if I could fly, I would do X.

98
00:05:19,973 --> 00:05:22,035
Or, you know, there's all these kind of scenarios

99
00:05:22,055 --> 00:05:22,775
we put ourselves through.

100
00:05:23,296 --> 00:05:23,496
And so,

101
00:05:24,645 --> 00:05:30,397
Through developing burgle bros, I've kind of got a system now that I use, and this wasn't

102
00:05:30,417 --> 00:05:33,022
all intentional, but this is the method that I came to, was that...

103
00:05:35,209 --> 00:05:40,412
You take a scene or a moment in what you're trying to,

104
00:05:40,992 --> 00:05:42,673
your source material, whatever that material is,

105
00:05:43,453 --> 00:05:45,995
and you peel it back, and you peel back,

106
00:05:46,035 --> 00:05:47,315
and you find at the nugget,

107
00:05:47,375 --> 00:05:49,836
what is the, at the best moment of that scene,

108
00:05:49,937 --> 00:05:51,597
what are you actually feeling?

109
00:05:52,158 --> 00:05:54,259
And then you try systems to recreate it.

110
00:05:54,299 --> 00:05:57,821
You try choices, and you try game systems,

111
00:05:58,001 --> 00:05:59,922
game mechanics to reproduce it.

112
00:06:00,282 --> 00:06:02,063
And it takes a lot of iteration to find something

113
00:06:02,083 --> 00:06:03,443
that can get the emotion that you want.

114
00:06:03,824 --> 00:06:08,067
Because anytime you create a system, there's going to be other things that, unintended consequences.

115
00:06:08,367 --> 00:06:14,051
So you gotta clean it up, and you gotta have to mitigate certain parts of that system that you don't really want.

116
00:06:14,872 --> 00:06:20,316
And then you tie it back into the theme. You're like, okay, if we have the system, what else would happen in that mechanic?

117
00:06:20,376 --> 00:06:22,878
And weave it back into your theme.

118
00:06:23,598 --> 00:06:28,962
And this is the method that I've kind of discovered with Bruegel Bros.

119
00:06:30,463 --> 00:06:30,583
So...

120
00:06:31,618 --> 00:06:34,179
I started with a hybrid game.

121
00:06:34,419 --> 00:06:39,121
I was working on an app that you interacted with a board game, and it was about a heist.

122
00:06:40,282 --> 00:06:47,145
And I went to Gen Con, I'm like, I'm demoing this game, and I'm like, because you go and

123
00:06:47,165 --> 00:06:49,366
you get people to playtest when you're a board game creator.

124
00:06:49,386 --> 00:06:52,088
You're like, okay, come play my game, and you've got to convince this guy that doesn't

125
00:06:52,128 --> 00:06:54,029
know who you are that this game is awesome.

126
00:06:54,049 --> 00:06:56,950
And I'm like, okay, it's like Ocean's Eleven, the board game.

127
00:06:57,030 --> 00:06:59,731
And their eyes lit up, and they're like, I want to play that game.

128
00:07:00,272 --> 00:07:04,317
And they'd come over and they'd play it, and the game was horrible, and I apologized to

129
00:07:04,377 --> 00:07:05,058
everybody that played it.

130
00:07:05,678 --> 00:07:07,120
Because it didn't fulfill that.

131
00:07:07,140 --> 00:07:09,403
But that put this bug in my head.

132
00:07:09,423 --> 00:07:11,525
I'm like, this is something people want.

133
00:07:11,565 --> 00:07:15,810
People want to live out a heist, and they want to know what choices they would make

134
00:07:15,850 --> 00:07:17,032
in that situation.

135
00:07:18,574 --> 00:07:18,794
So...

